column5:
for that spec, i can't really see past madinat for the dubai stay. you'll know you are in the middle east for sure.
for a short stay, i would normally suggest the szr from world trade centre to business bay as its about as central as it gets but i think for your age range, the jumeirah cluster of hotels close to mall of the emirates might be the best fit all round (disney style 'souk', waterpark, lots of restaurants, bars and its own beach too).
al maha in the desert is wonderful but they don't allow children (i am pretty sure) but bab al shams do - nice pool and they have mini golf and other kids activities. there are other desert resorts outside of dubai in rak and ad but they are quite long drives (qasr al sarab is set in wonderful dunes and is quite breathtaking) which might mean they are off the table.
shout if you need recommendations for desert (a nice private bbq away from the crowds would be my suggestion) and maybe a private city tour? used to organise events in the city so still have a few contacts that can help out. you'll have a blast!

column5:
i always liked the fisherman's village area before covid, i just like how it is nice and compact, and i'm not a big partier - it had everything i wanted, some nice restaurants and fairly quietish pubs to have a few drinks and watch a game of whatever sportsball is on. i've been pretty happy to hear the area is still doing ok through all this. but there's a good pick of hotels in the area to have a look at. since you have plenty of time before you need to book anything, it's fun to go through and look at hotels!

asif, starting thread short time skye.but comments road isles journey:

column5:
asif, you might be better starting your own thread about some short time on skye.but some comments on the road to the isles journey:
unless you're a train buff, i would take the car. the driving route follows the train route pretty much in terms of views but has the advantage of allowing you to stop and enjoy so much lovely scenery on route.
neptune's staircase is worth time if the views to the ben are clear as you get some really fine views of it from the canal.


the glenfinnan viaduct - there is a walking route to take you nearer it if of interest. great spot though you won't be alone in peak season.

my favourite views around glenfinnan are from the hotel itself (good for lunch as mentioned) and also from the beautiful st finnan's church nearby.


loch nan uamh has bonnie prince charlie connections too (similar to glenfinnan) - it's a beautiful sea loch with several places you can pull over for photos and just to drink in the views.
arisaig has a nice cafe down at the harbour where the boat to the small isles leaves.gets busy.
camusdarach i've already mentioned and the silver sands - to me, on a decent weather day, probably the highlights of the road to the isles.
i like mallaig though many don't rate it much - there isn't a whole lot to do in it as a final destination; a few cafes and restaurants and shops but it still has the fishing boats, the ferries come in to the harbour from the islands, seagulls keen overhead and skye sits tantalisingly across the sea.


that route along the road to the isles could easily take up a day, if you include lunch somewhere and some short strolls.easy enough too, to simply enjoy the unfolding scene, take some photos and make for skye.book the ferry well in advance.

column5:
i don’t know hyatt place very well but it’s well situated if you want to be in a traditional area and explore old dubai.
there are many eateries close to hand but note most are quite casual and not licensed to serve alcohol. if you drink alcohol then there many hotels in deira where you can head for a drink or a meal.
the chelsea arms at sheraton creek is one of the oldest pubs in dubai.
many hotels in deira offer shuttle buses to mamzar beach park - it has a lovely stretch of sandy beach but facilities are old and toilets leave a lot to be desired but for a cheap day out the beach, it can’t be overlooked.
i will say if you’re planning on golfing days and are staying at hyatt place then the creek golf course is closer and it has several bars & restaurants with amazing creek views.
i personally would look at splitting your stay between two hotels especially if you’re there for 10 nights, i’d do 5 nights in old dubai and head to the other side of dubai for 5 nights especially if you’re looking to visit the emirates golf course - somewhere like tecom/barsha heights or the marina may suit. even if you’re not a fan of more modern areas it’ll be easier for sightseeing in this area.
your itinerary sounds fine but jumeirah mosque and the marina aren’t next to each other, marina is accessible by metro but jumeirah mosque isn’t. i’d personally visit dubai frame and jumeirah mosque on the same day, taking a taxi between the two.
dubai frame is in zabeel park, not really out on a limb but not much else about.
unless you have an organised tour the mosque doesn’t take that long as you cannot just wander in at any given time.
if you like traditional areas then the souks at bur dubai and bastakiya is a must. al seef is also a really nice area to visit although it’s newly redeveloped it is very traditional in design.
edited: 6:11 pm, march 16, 2021

we walked with ease the vegas strip at midday and whilst phoenix was hotter it was manageable and we could eat outside with some degree of comfort , although most places did have misters .
no chance of that in dubai, its just to hot.
hotter than than and more uncomfortable would be singapore. ive never found the states that hot at that time ever.
a lot can be achieved in doors and early pm . dubai mall is really lovely in the pm so you could do burj khallifa before it gets dark then move on to the mall /fountains etc. its a huge mall with some highly expensive shops .
mall of the emirates is pretty standard now , but worth a trip if you want to ski at ski dubai.
atlantis and jumeriah beach are nice .

column5: self catering look at lakelovers and "heart of the lakes" (now jointly owned) and cumbrian cottages, you can select ones with swimming pool access, not many now though. some hotels allow you to book leisure day passes to go swimming, avoid the public swimming baths at troutbeck it gets very busy. nowhere is flat in the lakes to cycle except maybe the old keswick railway line, but ask before you hire, i'm sure they can give advice. brockhole on windermere has lots of activities for kids, they also used to do summer classes for adventure things but they book up very quickly. number one thing to do is the honister via ferrata, you will never forget the experience. for wet days (you will get them) kendal indoor climbing center is great, you can just have a drink and watch your child learn to climb safely, there is one at ambleside as well but not tried that, it is a lot smaller. we prefer ambleside as it is central for most places, it has craxy golf, putting, tennis as well and some easier walks, such as to grasmere. as someone said ambleside yha is good, best place in the lakes to sit outside and have a drink right on the lake, better than the pubs near by. platty kayaking on derwent is really good, make sure it is not a windy day though.

a comment on "cheap" dining with combini food (7/11), you might find it is not as cheap as you think. our experience is that it can be quick/easy after a tiring day sightseeing or working while on the road, and you can take it back to your room and relax and munch on what you get, but proper restaurants can offer decent food selections at a comparable price depending on the place. you pay a premium for the convenience.

>>>that depends sector involved. normally, tourism restaurants boost.<<<
from event lasts weeks, economy continues indefinitely - spot obvious mis-match. plus, thousands people avoid country hosts large events - south africa soccer world cup saw huge decline visitors across months hosted games.
there lot economic research separates fiction people promoting events, stadiums, benefits pro-team city reality. barcelona managed re-invigorate section city london made improvements, numbers stack up.
when working area, london olympics supposed generate 12billion pounds economic benefit pitched. year ahead games fallen billion, time event break-even.
some venues used except games. cycling velodrome cost 170 million pounds national cycling squad training.
even 1964 tokyo olympics - used venues used original purpose - filled swimming pool yoyogi - lol.
column5:
>>>that depends on the sector involved. normally, tourism and restaurants should get a boost.<<<
from an event that lasts a few weeks, and an economy that continues indefinitely - spot the obvious mis-match. plus, thousands of people avoid a country that hosts large events like these - south africa soccer world cup saw a huge decline in visitors across the months it hosted those games.
there is a lot of economic research that separates the fiction of the people promoting events, stadiums, the benefits of having a pro-team in their city and the reality. barcelona managed to re-invigorate a section of their city and london made some improvements, but really the numbers don't stack up.
when i was working in this area, the london olympics were supposed to generate 12billion pounds of economic benefit when pitched. a year ahead of the games that had fallen to one billion, and at the time of the event to maybe break-even.
some venues were not even used except for the games. the cycling velodrome cost 170 million pounds and the national cycling squad didn't even use it for training.
even the 1964 tokyo olympics - one of the most used venues i know of is not even used in its original purpose - they filled in the swimming pool at yoyogi - lol.
column8: 80 % favor for Olympics cancel and postpone

day trip imaicho (traditional old town) umami kyuryo botanical park (beautiful fields tulips spring) stop nara park feed deer;

column5:
thanks to all for your great posts!
dli_nk - thank you for sharing stunning fall photos.
william512 - also enjoyed your pictures. sakura bloom shots were wonderful, and your flower field pictures inspired me to add the two locations to our trip!
global1715255 - i thought your link to the intro to kabuki was helpful, and will get my husband to watch it before the trip. on your suggestion, i also added an overnight stay at ine fishing village.
hfot2 - my husband and i love easy, scenic bike rides like the kibi plain trail. in okayama, can korakuen gardens and kurashiki visit be combined in one day (mar 29) without overdoing it? if yes, we can then do the bike ride on mar 30, so we can take as much time as we want on the ride. the only other thing we are doing that day is driving to iya valley in late afternoon.
after more research i decided to forego the noto peninsula days, primarily because its not the right time to see the rice fields (flooded in late apr), and i really like the idea of overnighting in ine. i also spent time reading about shikoku. it was hard to decide what to see and what to leave out. i found that the matsuyama spring festival may happen while we are there, so focused on that area and iya valley. here's the latest itinerary version, with more detail added. still need to fill in tokyo, and then work on hotel/travel details.
mar 24 (thu) depart us
mar 26 arrive osaka from us.
mar 26-28 osaka (2 nts)
mar 26 visit kuromon ichiba market (energetic and fun food market), ebisu-bashi bridge (very crowded, iconic picture), nishinomaru garden (cherry blossoms), dotonburi food tour in evening.
mar 27 sumo tournament with guide in edion arena, osaka (this is last day of tournament, expect tickets to be hard to get, advanced tickets on sale beginning feb 6, 2022). go with guide to explain matches, request chair seats, second floor in section a, pref. first row on inner end. (closer box seats are cushions on floor, must sit cross legged for long periods.) typical match schedule runs from 8 am to 6 pm. 2:20 pm - juryo (all prof wrestlers) entrance ceremony, followed by their matches. 3:45 pm – makuuchi (top division wrestlers) entrance ceremony, followed by their matches. 6 pm – competition ends.
after the tournament, have dinner in hozenji yokocho alley – short, narrow, cobbled alleyway with local restaurants next to dotonburi street. while in hozenji yokocho, stop by hozenji temple with famous moss-covered buddha.
mar 28 depart from osaka to okayama. enroute stop at awaji hanasajiki garden (fields of yellow flowers in late march), and himeji castle (beautiful view of castle in spring, do not go inside castle – many stairs and empty).
mar 28-30 okayama (2 nts)
mar 29 okayama - visit korakuen gardens – one of 3 best gardens in japan. visit kurashiki (canal boat ride and/or walk, historical quarter, ½ day).
mar 30 am kibi plain bike trail (flat, scenic trail, allow ½ day or more, bring food and drink for picnic lunch). late pm drive (3 hrs) from okayama to iya valley.
mar 30 – apr 4 shiboku island (5 nts)
mar 30 - apr 1 iya valley (2 nts) iya onsen hotel; vine bridges; old farming villages (ochiai village, togenkyo iya village); oboke-koboke gorges’ cruise (boarding at obokekyo mannaka – 40 min drive from iya valley, 30 min boat ride); statue of peeing boy (shouben kozou).
apr 1 drive from iya valley to matsuyama (2 hrs)
apr 1-4 matsuyama (3 nts) dogo onsen stay.
apr 2 (sat) matsuyama spring festival (held every first weekend in april from fri to sun)
apr 3 (sun) day trip: drive from matsuyama to uichiko village (48 min drive), then ozu village (20 min from uichiko). possible to include drive to shikoku karst?
apr 4 depart from matsuyama to takamatsu (2 hrs) for a visit to ritsurin gardens and lunch of udon noodles. after lunch, drive to kyoto (3 ½ hrs).
apr 4 - 9 kyoto (5 nts):
kinkaku-ji temple (golden pavilion) and gardens just before closing to avoid crowds and for good photography light;
fushimi inari shrine (1000s of red gates, explore bottom area otherwise many, many steps to the top);
kiyomizudera temple - 6-8 am to avoid crowds;
[i know kyoto is famous for its temples, but we are not really temple enthusiasts, so would like to limit temples in kyoto to a few special ones, if possible.]
walk through tenryu-ji temple garden to arashimyama bamboo grove (before 8 am); then walk the higashiyama district early am before it fills with crowds;
walk saga toriimoto preserved street; ishibe alley; ninen-zaka and sannen-zaka streets;
visit heian jingu garden if peak sakura (these cherry trees bloom a little later than others in kyoto, around the tail end of the season, usually mid-april);
visit nishiki market – am, expect it to be very crowded and narrow;
walk along the philosopher's walk (follows canal lined by cherry trees);
geiko-maiko dance performance at kobu kaburenjo theater (obtain ticket well in advance);
kabuki play – try to arrange if one is playing at kyoto minamiza theater while we are in kyoto. dynamic (where actors move more) performances more entertaining than static. schedule not available yet;
private tea ceremony;
visit gion district, 10 course kaiseki meal/foodie tour;
dine in ponto-cho – atmospheric dining area, narrow alley with restaurants;
day trip to imaicho (traditional old town) and umami kyuryo botanical park (beautiful fields of tulips in spring) with stop at nara park to feed deer;
apr 10 depart from kyoto to ine fishing village.
apr 10-11 ine fishing village (1 nt). overnight in boathouse. local fishing private boat tour with guide. bike.
apr 11 depart from ine to kanazawa
apr 11-13 kanazawa (2 nts) - omicho market, kenrokuen garden, visit ainokura gassho comm (and gokayama). check to see if asanogawa enukai festival in kanazawa happens during our visit (traditional dances and other entertainment held on a floating stage).
apr 13 bus to takayama, stopping at shirakawa-go.
apr 13-15 takayama (2 nts)
apr 14-15 (thurs-fri) takayama spring festival (sanno matsuri) – street display of festival floats decorated with sophisticated mechanical dolls (karakuri) that move and dance, karakuri performance at set times during the day, mikoshi procession, evening festival (festival floats are pulled through old town for 2-3 hours, considered festival highlight). festival is very popular, visited by several hundred thousand people. considered to be 1 of 3 most beautiful festivals in japan.
apr 15 before 11 am, depart takayama to matsumoto. visit matsumoto castle – exterior only. the inside has steep, deep steps that may be difficult if knee issues (need about 2 hours for visit). after matsumoto, head to lake kawaguchi-ko.
apr 15-16 lake kawaguchi-ko (1 nt)
apr 16 spend the day at lake: bike ride around lake – takes approx. 3 hours with stops, 20 min boat ride on lake for great views – possibility to see mt. fuji. later in the afternoon, travel to tokyo. if lucky, may be right time for annual spring festival.
apr 16-19 tokyo (3 nts).
apr 17-18 visit tsukiji fish market (go just before 9 am to avoid crowds), need to read alot more about tokyo.
apr 19 fly home

column5:
hi,
first to note to avoid any confusion that the kembali villas you listed in post #3 (perhaps it was an auto link) is not kembali beach bungalows in amed.
kembali villas linked in post #3 are in seminyak.
do you dive or just snorkeling.
pemuteran
check exact location of any property carefully. pemuteran spreads out a long way also inland.
pemuteran is mrs pigs favourite after amed.
we stay at 
you have to walk down the beach a little to enter the sea for snorkeling. main reasons is that their are a lot of sea urchins in the sea along with low lying reefs close to shore. there is a signpost.
entry is more or less in front of the pondok sari.
you will also find the biorock reef restoration project.
the only thing is that pemuteran bay is very sandy (just offshore). at full moon/spring tides/windy/choppy seas the sand can get churned up in the bay. even snorkeling close to shore it can be like snorkeling in a milkshake. literally can’t see your hand in front of your face. biorock not visible.
i’ve been diving well offshore and when in shallower water 10-15m on a sunny day it was like diving in a snowglobe with all the glistening sand.
i use the dive centre on the beach behind the swimming pool/wellness massage centre.

they have 2 dive boats. one rib and one larger fibreglass hull boat.
if only snorkeling you can enquire at the dive centre or others along the beach, about snorkeling trips menjangan.
dive trips often willing to take snorkelers if space. advantage is the boat goes from the beach.
you can arrange snorkeling trips locally but this may involve a road trip in a minibus before picking up a local boat.
out on the main singaraja road you will find a few restaurants geared up for tourists. we particularly like warung tirta sari at tirta sari bungalows opposite suka sari bungalows and warung.
also nearby selini bakery does some nice cakes.

column5: yep, i'm back in london every november for over a decade, and it really sucks. this year i was thinking at the start of summer things might be looking good finally. now i'm just about to give up and realize it'll now be year 2 in a row of not going back. i miss my football matches, i miss my pubs and i miss exploring new areas of the city as well as towns outside the metro area and most of all, i miss my damn eels and seafood stalls on the road in the east end...

column5:
strongly recommend the last few nights at sanur, rather than benoa.
it is very easy to connect with the charming locals and get up close and personal with some of the local culture. there are beachfront restaurants and charming small warungs, where you can sit with your feet in the sand and gaze out to sea watching the fisherman standing chest deep in the calm water, as you drink cold beer and eat fresh fish or spicy noodles.......doesn't get any better.
when you're ready for exercise, the beachfront walking path offers kilometres of sea views and bali life all around you,and the opportunity for endless stops along the way for bbq corn, icecream or a cocktail.

column5:
did you rent a car, or just notice this in a taxi? driving is different here. i shudder to think of the resulting disarray if you allowed left turns when oncoming traffic had a green signal. wait for an appropriate opening? not likely. no, ... each direction has its own signal. and there are heavy penalties for going through a red light; drivers make every effort to stop. it's good for a laugh that stop signs are mere suggestions, however ...
somewhat unnerving driving in heavy fog also:

several courses near hua hin apart black mountain. group 50 something couples find hh much nicer place pattaya.

column5:
presumably southborough kent, uk ? if from the uk you will find thailand getting quite hot towards the end of february, particularly for a round of golf, and if you have flexibility i would go as early as possible that month rather than later.
several courses near to hua hin apart from black mountain. for me a group of 8 50 something couples would find hh a much nicer place than pattaya.
agree withmrc, chiang mai is a pleasant small city and almost entirely low rise. but by the end of february daytime maxima could be up around 35c and smoke haze could be a problem. the air quality at hh would probably be better at that time of year....though weather and pollution wise nothing is set in stone in thailand.

column4:
“ small window 3-4 months (june-sept), ride leh. roads blocked rest year.”
this wildly inaccurate, starting idea two inroads open/close time. last decade srinagar-leh opened march , final closure open often long december - twice early january. pics run early december - road closed , unsurprisingly, three weeks later :

manali-leh runs lot higher , closes earlier . snowfallls often mid-september , closure normally mid/late november . pics run made end-october :

roads within ladakh remain normally open thru winter . month long stay count days problems snowfall , quickly burns away sunny conditions.
rain occur nowadays early august , problem road trips.
“ indian citizens require permit visit ladakh..”
neither angrezis , 90+ percent ladakh & zanskar permit free areas . permits required :
* north leh ( nubra , tso moriri )
* northwest leh ( dha & hanu )
* east manali-leh road , close chinese border ( pangong tso )
column5:
“ there is a small window of 3-4 months (june-sept), when you can ride to leh. the roads are blocked during the rest of the year.”
this is wildly inaccurate, starting with the idea that the two inroads open/close at the same time. over the last decade srinagar-leh has opened between march and may , and final closure open often long in to december - twice in to early january. here some pics from a run in early december - road closed , unsurprisingly, three weeks later :

manali-leh runs a lot higher , and closes earlier . first snowfallls often in mid-september , closure normally around mid/late november . here some pics from a run i made end-october :

roads within ladakh remain normally open thru the winter . in a month long stay i count on a few days with problems from snowfall , that quickly burns away in sunny conditions.
rain does occur nowadays in sometimes around early august , and can be a problem on road trips.
“ indian citizens require no permit to visit ladakh..”
neither does angrezis , and 90+ percent of ladakh & zanskar is permit free areas . permits are required :
* north of leh ( nubra , tso moriri )
* northwest of leh ( dha & hanu )
* east of manali-leh road , close to chinese border ( pangong tso )

column4:
there
we spent month thailand feb 2020 children aged 11. amazing experience worthwhile them.
our itinerary was:
3 nights bangkok stayed ibis riverside (great family rooms)
2 nights khao yai stayed greenleaf afternoon tour 1st day full day tour 2nd day. amazing place greenleaf highly recommended. tours incredible saw wild elephants well much else.
next got train ayutthaya spent afternoon temple tour getting night train chiang mai.
7 nights chiang mai fabulous kids. highlights day karen tribe native elephants (cant recommended highly enough), sticky waterfalls, big game fishing, grand canyon water park.
then got direct flight krabi taxi koh lanta nights. koh lanta amazing family friendly. best day ever private long-tail trip koh rok, magical day life lanta paradise called. loved car hire going national park, mangrove kayaking trip.
after got speedboat koh mook nights. quiet pretty totally different vibe developed, real roads, 7/11, atm etc. loved here, put going hotel behind main beach knocked quite building site.
next got speedboat koh lipe nights. stayed castaway family house. stunning here, nowhere i've been. busier. snorkeling incredible water beautiful crystal clear turquoise colour. loved it.
then flew hat yai bangkok night heading home.
i love hesitate encourage others travel thailand young families. enjoy planning i'm envious!!!
column5:
hi there
we spent a month in thailand feb 2020 with our children aged 8 and 11. absolutely amazing experience and so worthwhile doing with them.
our itinerary was:
3 nights bangkok stayed at ibis riverside (great family rooms)
2 nights khao yai stayed at greenleaf and did the afternoon tour on 1st day then full day tour on 2nd day. absolutely amazing place and greenleaf is highly recommended. tours were incredible and we saw wild elephants as well as so much else.
next we got train to ayutthaya and spent afternoon on temple tour before getting night train to chiang mai.
7 nights at chiang mai which again absolutely fabulous with kids. highlights were day with karen tribe native elephants (cant recommended highly enough), sticky waterfalls, big game fishing, grand canyon water park.
then we got direct flight to krabi and taxi to koh lanta for 5 nights. koh lanta amazing and very family friendly. best day ever was a private long-tail trip to koh rok, most magical day of my life with lanta paradise i think was called. also loved car hire and going to national park, and mangrove kayaking trip.
after this we got speedboat to koh mook for 3 nights. very quiet but very pretty and a totally different vibe as not at all developed, no real roads, no 7/11, no atm etc. loved it here, only thing put me off going back was a hotel behind main beach been knocked down and was quite a building site.
next got speedboat to koh lipe for 4 nights. stayed at castaway in family house. absolutely stunning here, like nowhere else i've been. but busier. snorkeling incredible and the water the most beautiful crystal clear turquoise colour. loved it.
then flew from hat yai to bangkok for 1 more night before heading home.
i would love to do it again and would not hesitate to encourage others to travel to thailand with young families. enjoy the planning i'm very envious!!!
column8: Jungle + Beach with children... ideas welcome!

column4:
leh-pangong tso-leh single day gives little time vehicle. going directly tso´s leh staying overnight outside safety guidelines , worse spent least three nights 3000+ meters ( # ) , medicating advance . option overnighting tangtse ( higher leh , lower pangong tso ) , tso return leh next day.
warm winter far . chaddar trek stopped feb 7th. got message school phey yesterday : last hockey match season. weather forecast shows zero leh tangtse @ 3950 meters coming days - shade , warmer sun.
column5:
leh-pangong tso-leh in a single day gives little time out of the vehicle. going directly to the tso´s from leh and staying overnight is outside safety guidelines , this is even worse if you haven't spent at least like three nights at 3000+ meters ( like in # 1 ) , and are not medicating in advance . one option is to overnighting at tangtse ( higher than leh , lower than pangong tso ) , do the tso and return to leh next day.
warm winter this far . chaddar trek stopped feb 7th. i got a message from the school in phey yesterday : last hockey match of the season. weather forecast shows just above zero in leh and tangtse @ 3950 meters the coming days - in the shade , so even warmer in the sun.

august gone, weeks.

column5:
we were there august just gone, for 2 weeks.
we sat around the pool during the day, but you’re literally in the pool every 1/2 hour or so, which isn’t a problem tbh, so it’s imperative that your hotel has a great pool area imo. too hot for the beach as the sea is too warm to enjoy properly. absolutely no chance of eating outdoors or an evening. the most we lasted outdoors of an evening (other than at the desert safari) was watching the fountain show at the burj khalifa. then straight back indoors.
you couldn’t walk around more than 20-30minutes (ish) during the daytime either.
this didn’t stop us having a great holiday, we did most of the touristy things such as desert safari, jet skis, ferrari world, atlantis water park, malls, burj khalifa, madinat, le perle, etc.
doing these things break the holiday up nicely, especially as long days in the sun do take their toll in dubai, more than other holiday destinations do in august.
would i go again in august; probably not if i could go a different time.
would i go if that’s the only time i could go; yes.

column4:
i’ve used luffield can’t help but..
you’ll find spend lot time watching race big screens (or ipad) well what’s front decent view screen important - silverstone pancake flat seeing across circuit near impossible). high won’t achieve much viewing puts action, win it’s raining you’ll drier it’s blazing sun there’s shade - doubt matters i’d want dozen rows front cover weather extremes.
a f1 race relatively long event there’s natural ‘half time’ drivers parade end toll bladders folk race (or lot of) beers (and quite them). sit end row you’ll jumping let visit facilities monotonous regularity, sit middle struggle call nature. choice!
ot, want watch motor race rather ‘be there’ brands hatch offers viewing experience.
column5:
i’ve not used luffield so can’t help there but..
you’ll find you spend a lot of time watching the race on the big screens (or your ipad) as well as what’s in front of you so a decent view of a screen is important - silverstone is pancake flat so seeing across the circuit is near impossible). high up won’t achieve much more viewing and puts you i bit further from the action, the win is that if it’s raining you’ll be drier and if it’s blazing sun there’s some shade - i doubt it matters but i’d want to be a dozen rows back from the front to cover weather extremes.
a f1 race is a relatively long event and there’s no natural ‘half time’ so from drivers parade to the end will take its toll on the bladders of the folk who go to the race with a few (or a lot of) beers (and there will be quite a few of them). if you sit at the end of a row you’ll be jumping up to let them visit the facilities with monotonous regularity, if you sit in the middle it will be a struggle if you get the call of nature. your choice!
ot, but if you want to watch a motor race rather than just ‘be there’ brands hatch offers a better viewing experience.

column5:
himachal pradesh is my dream destination not only for being home of three shakti peeth or being the playground of gods and goddess (dev bhumi) but for its enchanting nature and beauty. from childhood i am attracted to the mountains of himachal. at very young age have trekked hampta pass, rohtang pass and fell in love. now after 30 years i want to fulfill my dream of going around and absorb as much as himachal pradesh.
must for me: naina devi temple , maa chintpurni temple , shaktipeeth shri bajreshwari devi temple
my interest - i want to cover all the shakti peeths in the area, important and historic temples, gurudwaras, buddhist monastery, mosque and church in this region. i enjoy trekking and nature.
this is my 28 days itinerary to go to himachal pradesh from delhi in june of 2021.

exactly ms sturgeon said but, joking aside, sensible approach here. rather lockdowns freedom, can't advise people common sense? understand official line i'd planned meet friend leeds manchester lunch ahead. thinking day shopping, chester instead. i'd arranged visit someone nice day, stay garden to. see lot rampaging football fans, difference behave. millions people similar fall right side knife edge moment.

column5:
i don't know exactly what ms sturgeon has said but, joking aside, i like to think there is a sensible approach here. rather then having lockdowns or freedom, can't you advise people to use common sense? as i understand it the official line for me is if i'd planned to meet a friend from leeds in manchester for lunch then go ahead. if i was just thinking of a day out shopping, maybe go to chester instead. if i'd arranged to visit someone and it's a nice day, maybe stay in the garden even though you don't have to. if you see a lot of rampaging football fans, that doesn't make any difference to how you should behave. and if millions of people do similar things we fall the right side of the knife edge we seem to be on at the moment.
for the op, that means go ahead with the perfectly safe and reasonable plans you have made. but if you were booking it today, maybe think of flying to and from edinburgh.

column5:
it’s a myth that fish has to be caught ‘same day’ to be best to eat
it depends on species / size and of course how long the fishing boat was at sea before the catch was landed, but some (especially larger) fish are better ‘hung’ before eating as sashimi.

column5:
hi fellow travelers -
my husband and i are planning a may 2022 honeymoon to indonesia and would really appreciate some help with the itinerary (side note: we got married just before the pandemic, but the pandemic and other circumstances have pushed our first trip as "newlyweds" to 2022!) there is obviously so much to see and so many islands, but we are mindful of not cramming in too much. my pandemic wanderlust is making decisions very difficult though!
budget isn't really an issue and we'd like to spend a solid two weeks in-country, not including travel time. we could even extend this by a couple days beyond 14 days if need be, with all that vacation time we will have saved up by then!
we really want to split the trip - first half exploring breathtaking nature, culture/temples, having unique experiences and adventures (nothing too strenuous, but moderate hiking/biking/snorkeling are definitely our speed), and the second half really relaxing and continuing to take in breathtaking natural beauty (away from lots of tourists! we would like to get off the beaten path, but understand that can be hard with only two-ish weeks).
we're currently thinking:
1) 7 days exploring bali (specifically, ubud and northern and eastern bali. we don't care to visit bali's kuta or any of the super touristy areas, nor do we care about nightlife)
2) 3-4 days exploring lombok (specifically, staying in southern lombok at one of the beaches near lombok's kuta. perhaps road tripping with a driver/guide to the east and/or west and stopping to explore local villages and culture? we're not quite up for the mount rinjani crater rim hike, but beaches in southern lombok with a luxury villa sound nice to us. we still want to explore though, not just sit on a beach - does anyone have suggestions for worthwhile things to check out on lombok?)
3) 3-4 days at mayahana resort on gili meno - this is all the time we need to seriously do nothing but chill on a beach :)
4) return for one last night in bali before heading home.
what do you think of the plan above? are the days distributed well? anything that should be adjusted/swapped out?
i'd also love recommendations for how to best explore lombok.
lastly, will we be missing out by not getting to sumatra, java, and/or flores? are any of these places more "worthwhile" to be swapped out with lombok/gili meno? we originally were looking at exploring flores/komodo, but we don't scuba dive (only snorkel) and it seemed less practical than lombok in terms of travel logistics. feedback and suggestions would be really, really appreciated! thanks!!

column5:
>>so does anyone in singapore at the moment seen any sign of preparation for this event<<
you won't see anything until much closer in time - not physically anyway. its remarkable how fast everything gets put up and down - plus it ha been scheduled later this year in the first weekend of october.
so, your first signals for the race will be online - currently the official site isnt listing tickets for sale

it will be here that you get the first inklings of the race and so i would hook up to the news from that site plus the overall f1 core site for getting the latest information on ticketing.
you can then try and steer plans around that.
however if singapore is still a small bubble, or even opening up but isn't open to people who have been in your base country then it will still be effectively out of reach.
more importantly, they may not have a waiver allowing a refund if its simply your country of residence being barred while many others are being allowed in. so you need to think about the terms and conditions on the tickets before buying in relation to how singapore is opening up to the outside world.

chiang mai is a big little city, its core is all low rise, with just a couple of small high rise districts on nimmehaemin and around festival shopping mall. living here is more like an old country town than a modern big city. there are several golf courses outside the city in rural areas. and lots of great food options.

column5:
agree completely with shaun. frame is an easy one to do on your own and is simple to get a taxi to it and the metro back if you fancied. join that up with a trip into the older part of town for instance and its a nice afternoon or evening.
lots advice on miracle garden by bus has been posted over the years but taxi would be my suggestion and pair it with something at that end of the city - perhaps lunch at emirates golf club or a wander around mall of the emirates or jumeriah madinat.
shaun will often say that a couple of hours on google maps laying out your todo list is invaluable. as the city is long and thin, get things in the wrong order and you will spend a lot of time and money in taxis racing up and down the szr!
another option would be to have a driver for the day when you have lots on. sometimes it makes more sense to know you have a car waiting as you leave an attraction and have somewhere to leave bags etc when you are inside. when i organised events, dubai your way (where we supplied couples with a good driver) was a popular part of the tour itinerary.

column4:
tryp isn’t bad shout 5-10 minutes metro depending fast walk!
mecure close & grand millenium closer you’ll pay privilege. you’re heading golf course you’ll getting taxi convenient base getting courses.
when side dubai well golfing visits marina, palm, ibn battuta ( heading ad), miracle garden, mall emirates makes sense visit part dubai.
it’s little quicker dubai mall via metro tryp baniyas square you’re line it’s easy enough either.
hyatt place convenient deira souks & creek golf course, metro ( green line) straight al fahidi baniyas square alternatively cheap abra across creek explore old dubai.
as jumeirah mosque tryp head al sufouh jumeirah beach road, passing lovely hotels, palace guest houses, jumeirah district it’s quite pleasant drive it’s 25 minute drive.
from baniyas square, theory quicker 15 minutes traffic busy along creek road peak times. alternatively bus baniyas square longer cheap chips.
column5:
tryp isn’t a bad shout about 5-10 minutes to the metro depending how fast you walk!
mecure is very close & i think grand millenium will be a bit closer but you’ll pay more for the privilege. if you’re heading to the golf course then you’ll be getting a taxi but this is a very convenient base for getting to most courses.
when over this side of dubai as well as golfing visits to the marina, palm, ibn battuta ( if heading to ad), miracle garden, mall of the emirates makes sense to visit when this part of dubai.
it’s probably a little quicker to get to dubai mall via metro from tryp than baniyas square and you’re on the same line but it’s easy enough from either.
hyatt place is more convenient for deira souks & creek golf course, you can get the metro ( green line) straight to al fahidi from baniyas square alternatively take a cheap abra across the creek and explore old dubai.
as for jumeirah mosque from tryp you can head down al sufouh and jumeirah beach road, passing some lovely hotels, palace guest houses, once you get into the jumeirah district then it’s quite a pleasant drive but it’s about a 25 minute drive.
from baniyas square, it should in theory be quicker about 15 minutes but traffic can be busy along the creek road in peak times. alternatively get a bus from baniyas square which will take a bit longer but will be cheap as chips.

column5:
the ministry of health reported at 6am 29/1, 9 more cases, 91 in total: 4 more in hai duong and 2 more in quang ninh; and the other 3 in bac ninh, hai phong and hanoi (hai ba trung). not 100 yet though there certainly will be more.
there are 2 suspected cases in soc son and tay ho in hanoi with close contacts in several districts including hoan khiem. in hai phong, the next largest city after hanoi, 22 f1 cases are isolated in hospitals and 222 f2 isolated and managed at home. a high level of prevention measures are in force.

the contract tracers are very busy, identifying in some areas contacts up to f4, doing their best to contain these outbreaks quickly. according to a nature article last month, vietnam had 12000 trained contact tracers at the start of the pandemic. there are interesting comparisons with other countries.

regards

column5:
we’ve been coming to the lakes for the last 8 or so years and our kids are always happy when we stay in ambleside.
plenty of walks 12 year old could manage from here so you wouldn’t need to drive one or two days. can access the windermere ferry from waterhead also brockhole easy to get to.
if wet day or evening activity then there is a choice of cinemas. putting green and crazy golf if that’s your thing.
activities we’ve done from this base have included both go apes (whinlatter and grizedale).
i’d say your 12 year old is probably too old for the lakes aquarium now.
summer 2019 we stayed in lorton which gave easy access to keswick area but we also were able to get out to the coast and avoid the crowds.
i’d suggest avoiding windermere in the school holidays if you can.
enjoy. thinking our trip at easter is looking much less likely having fingers crossed for a summer trip.

best route plan follows
# arrive dehradun, stop rishikesh, relax next day early morning head auli
# 10 hrs reach auli, need reach comfortably time cable car, wish reach auli top, stay joshimath
# later drive break rishikesh drive straight mussoorie, depending comfort

column5:
your best route plan would be as follows
# arrive at dehradun, make a stop at rishikesh, relax and next day early morning head out to auli
# it will take you about 10 hrs to reach auli, and you need to reach before 3 pm to comfortably be in time to take cable car, if you wish to reach the auli top, else you can stay at joshimath
# later drive down and either take a break at rishikesh or drive straight to mussoorie, depending on your comfort
however all said and done, why would you want to do mussoorie, after getting an overdose and the best of it during your 10 hours road trip and subsequent stay at auli. it would only be repetitive, and tiring.
i can suggest you rather opting for rajaji national park, closer to rishikesh to explore more and have a diverse experience.

column5:
#214 - just because someone lives near enough to travel frequently for short trips does not make their visitor stats double counted. each visit is a visit.
if you are going to assign count value based on distance traveled, then americans and canadians should get double because it is 20-28 hours flying time versus eu & uk at 12ish. if you are going to assign count value based on duration of visit, then we expats have you all beat hands down and twice around the block. no, a visit is a visit, period.
no group of tourists is more important. each tourist is an individual with their own spending, their own time in country, their own number of return visits, etc. a japanese business man popping down for a weekend of golf is just as important as a uk gap year backpacker nickel & dime'ing their way across the country.

column5:
i would say 2 days in edinburgh unless you plan say, a day's tour of the highlands. something like this will take you through some great west highland scenery:

however not necessarily rabbies - there are other operators too though tours tend to be whistlestop so might not suit your need for a slower pace.
the glasgow to fw train journey gives you several very good options for breaking the journey for a day or so to enjoy some beautiful places:
for example, you could stop and overnight around tarbert on loch lomond, a tiny place but where there is an excellent boat trip on the loch to inversnaid.eating out though is limited and arrochar next door would be your best bet, using a taxi. otherwise, staying somewhere like pretty luss village also on the loch, would be another great option (no train station .potentially taxi from a nearby station if that can be arranged.local hotels might help with that.)
then resume your train journey north with another potential stop at corrour - most remote station in uk, gorgeous environment, great bistro right at the station, excellent accommodation too and the chance to do flattish walks by loch ossian.

then resume journey to fort william.the scenery to fw is stunning.
you can certainly carry on to mallaig too - not a lot in mallaig , a down to earth wee fishing/ferry port, but i personally like it for a short time, with great views to skye too (which you could potentially go over too also - magnificent island.bus to portree or stay in south skye around isle ornsay perhaps (eilean iarmain hotel is in a gorgeous spot.)

you could return via bus from fw will would also allow a stop at glencoe - perhaps staying overnight in the kingshouse hotel, right on rannoch moor amidst stunning scenery. nothing else there except red deer and the river, moor and mountains.

column5:
whilst i would usually agree with those that advocate spending 3 nights in a place on the basis that will allow two full days of actually seeing stuff, there are occasions when on a road trip, i would be quite happy moving on each day. sometimes, the journey can be as rewarding as the destinations, especially on a motorcycle or driving trip when you can, and will want to, stop at places along the way.
when we did the trip from mai chau to ninh binh we had planned to spend 3 days in mai chau as we loved it when we first stayed the 15-20 years ago. it had changed a lot. the two homestays that were there back then had multiplied to something like 50. to get the authentic experience you seek, i would suggest getting way out into the valley away from the main settlements. ninh binh needs 3 nights to see the main sights, take a few boat trips etc. . both mc and nb get very busy with domestic tourists especially at weekends so time your visits mid week if possible.
in between the two locations we spent one night at each of three small villages. these one night stays were about right as we were mainly hiking (and part driving) between each. on a motorbike with a guide i can imagine it would be a great experience .
if you can add in some extra days, have you consider the caves in phong nha ke be? well worth tif you can add in maybe three nights en route from hue to ninh binh by train.quite a lot else to do in teh area other than the cave (although they are amazing!)
as for traveling by train, it is my preferred option in vietnam. not the most comfortable but ok i would recommend going for a soft sleeper berth (bottom bunk if you can). my understanding is that the schedules have been dramatically curtailed, when they will return to normal. two benefits of train travel; they are usually overnight and you save on a nights accommodation. most live late evening and arrive early morning effectively allowing a full day at either end.

column5:
i cut things short in the end, in part because of the weather (and it being too cold to camp !), and in part because i've got through most of the things i wanted to do anyway.
actual itinerary was vaguely as below:
day 0 - travel up to inverness
day 1 - bus to ullapool, ferry to stornoway, pick up hire car, drive to harris. wild camped (freezing).
day 2 - looking about harris. slept in the eagle observatory hut (probably even more freezing than the tent).
day 3 - ferry to berneray. quick look round berneray, drive round a few places in the uists, b&b in benbecula.
day 4- banranland and griminish point (swam in the sea :) brrrr ), b&b on benbecula
day 5 - walked a few holes at askernish golf course, had a look around eriskay including walking up the biggest hill, b&b on benbecula
day 6 - ferry to skye. walked up to an around old man of storr. b&b in broadford.
day 7 - drove to the lochalsh peninsula on the mainland, and down to armissdale and corron where i went for a wee walk, before getting the tiny wee ferry back over from glenelg to skye. checked out the otter hide. drove to elgol and walked around a bit. walked from camasunary car park up to the top. drove to portree for a look around. drove to dungevan and camped.
day 8 - walked the loop at the quirang, beating a major snowstorm by minutes. had a quick peek at the kilted cliff, found a nice b&b in portree.
day 9 - ferry back to harris. quick walk on luskentyre beach before heading up to lewis to check out uig sands, kneep, the callindish stones, and a few other stops along the way
day 10 - cleaned the car out and returned it before getting a glorious ferry ride back to ullapool which was bathed in beautiful sunshine. hotel in inverness.
day 11 - early train home
distance driven : 1002 miles.
highlights:
- the walk to traigh na cleavag from northton (harris)
- balranald & griminish point (benbecula)
- the quirang and old man of storr (skye)
trip costs (excluding gear for camping (haha) and hiking):
- car hire and fuel £440
- other transport (trains, buses, ferries) £350
- accommodation £ 520
- living expenses and other costs £250
total £1,560
photos to follow.
edited: 4:14 am, may 08, 2021

thanks for the heads up everybody. yes, i did think that the motorhome might be a bit of a challenge, what with all the single lane roads on mull. although to be fair, not just mull, many roads in the highlands are like that. and the fact is, many people are taking to the road in a motorhome these days. we had considered, before being offered the loan of this motorhome, doing a road trip, staying in b&b's. until that is, i discovered the world and his wife are staying in b&b accommodation this year, and the prices are outrageous if you can find somewhere.
i understand the tourist industry is very complicated, having once lived in a 'touristy' area. we needed them because it was pretty much the only way to make a living.
as of yet, we haven't really made any decisions. if we do decide on mull, then i recognise we are going to have to book quite a while ahead, and may still be disappointed. then again, mull isn't going anywhere, and neither are we (we hope), so there will always be another year.

column5:
thanks for the replies. i saw myrm suggested a stream - i'd never dream of doing such a thing ;)
for anyone else interested, i actually contacted changi and didn't expect a reply, at least so quickly - but here is the official reponse:
thank you for your enquiry sent on 07 june 2021.
changi airport has implemented safety measurement measures in which transit passengers will be segregated to 2 different piers within the departure transit hall depending on the countries that they will be arriving from - unilateral opening (uo) countries (lower risk) and non- unilateral opening (non- uo) countries (higher risk).
transit passengers that are arriving from non- uo countries will be escorted from their arrival gate to the transit holding area (tha) to wait for their connecting flight. and they will not be allowed to leave the tha unless if they have a confirmation for a room reservation at our transit hotels - aerotel transit hotel (terminal 1) or ambassador transit hotel (terminal 3).
and for transit passengers that are arriving from uo countries, although they will not be escorted upon arrival, they will not be allowed to leave their piers. kindly also note that due to the airport closure to the public until the 13 june 2021, only certain retail stores, f & b outlets and facilities/ services will continue to operate. hence, we regret to inform that there is no facility at changi airport for you to watch the football game during your layover in singapore.
i hope that the information provided clarifies your enquiry. please do not hesitate to contact us if you have any further questions.

- attempt walk green channel prohibited, restricted dutiable goods

column5:
>> what happens if someone coming from uk carries over 2 lakh of foreign currency (after converting it to inr) <<
the link and the answer is already provided in the thread. 
nothing happens. two lakh is barely $3000 us, so it is well within the limit.
any person can bring into india from a place outside india foreign exchange without any limit. however, declaration of foreign exchange/ currency is required to be made in the prescribed currency declaration form in the following cases:-
(a) where the value of foreign currency notes exceeds us $5,000/- or equivalent
(b) where the aggregate value of foreign exchange (in the form of currency notes, bank notes, traveller cheques etc.) exceeds us $10,000/- or its equivalent
>> without a declaration from the customs. can they detain such traveller or what are the rules for not having declaration? <<
for the sake of completeness ...
penal provisions
please note that non-declaration, mis-declaration and concealment of imported goods are offences under the customs act, 1962 which may result in confiscation, fine, penalty and even prosecution.
the customs act, 1962 also empowers imposition of heavy penalties for those passengers who:
- attempt to walk through the green channel with prohibited, restricted or dutiable goods
- mis-declare their goods at the red channel
- attempt to export prohibited or restricted goods.
- abet the commission of any of the above offences.
the penal action may lead to:
- absolute confiscation of goods or imposition of heavy fine in respect of the concerned goods if these are released
- imposition of penalty on individuals or concerned entities
- arrest and prosecution including invocation of preventive detention in serious cases.
column8: Foreign Exchange limit while coming into India.

column5:
had a bit of refreshing rain ourselves this very early am, actually woke me up. aqi @ high 20's @ 0700 hrs, now low 20's almost 3 hrs later. dispelling any implications that local pollution issue is blown in from afar; myanmar or cambodia. quite easy to tell when entering our little valley on hwy #4, and seeing the plumes of smoke in the distance.
20's reading differing greatly from aqi site, as was and still is showing aqi of high 80's / low 90's. so no idea where their meter is, but certainly not 'local'.
as stated, aqi sites are just a reference, and the larger metros with more meters are better gauge, than here, small fishing village and farming valley.
better to google 'private' folks, possible extremely intelligent and handsome, that maintain a site / page with their own local readings .... 555
hopefully the damp ground will keep things under 100 the rest of the month, as had a horrendous 160 the other day, and could barely see the headland at both ends of the bay from the balcony, or the hills to the west. if not knowing there, you wouldn't have been able to make out the outline of first ridge.
be safe ... and plan wisely, using every resource you can, to ensure a happy holiday.

column4:
tourists allowed country, required quarantine 15 nights, start playing tourist 16th day country. done quarantine free travel wherever wish within thailand. plan month long stay (or longer) worth it, short stays practical yet.
the online posts news resort bubbles misleading ideas that, ideas. never made fruition. closest got approved "golf quarantine" allowed room day play round golf quarantine period.
sadly bloggers news media bother updating stories whether ideas got approved. simply leave wishful thinking causing confusion.
column5:
tourists are allowed in the country, but they are required to quarantine for 15 nights, you start playing tourist on your 16th day in country. but once done with quarantine you are free to travel wherever you wish within thailand. if you plan a month long stay (or longer) it maybe worth it, but short stays are not practical yet.
the online posts and news about resort bubbles are misleading as those ideas were just that, ideas. they never made it to fruition. the closest thing that got approved is "golf quarantine" where you are allowed out of your room once a day to play a round of golf by yourself during the quarantine period.
sadly bloggers and news media don't bother updating stories as to whether or not the ideas got approved. they simply leave the wishful thinking out there causing confusion.

column5:
in farmed areas, esp near still water, another species of insect is much more common and does often get mistaken for midges as they are similar size (usually slightly smaller) and mainly appear towards dusk, in huge midgie-like swarms. i've usually encountered them when out fishing but they don't bite us so much less of an issue. deet sort-of works/helps but i can't say about i-cardin yet.
the advice above about lyme disease is very pertinent because it is on the rise in scotland and the strains most common here are the more full-on/unpleasant variety, so being aware of the signs is wise as it is fully treatable in its early stages.

column5:
i rec'd my first quarantine phone call today! very exciting after reading about it all for months (i am a subscriber to a british newspaper--after the tipping tempest, i won't name the paper).
they called at 11:30. her accent was very hard for me to understand, so i kept having to ask her to repeat herself. she sounded scottish, but some words sounded irish. finally i asked and she said she was from liverpool! i told her my husband is a huge liverpool soccer fan and his password for everything is liverpool-something. she said she, too, is a liverpool supporter.
she patiently repeated everything when i didn't understand. putting my phone on speaker helped me understand her.
i, too, was concerned about missing a call if i am in the shower or asleep (i woke up today at 11 am). she said not to worry; they might call back or call the next day. i don't think they come looking for you unless you don't answer.
they have a whole script they read. they confirm a few things and that's it.
*for the person who asked about the airport procedure/test: i'm going back to my first post to reply to you to give you info.
please feel free to ask any questions about my experience so far (i've got a whole lot of nothing going on...haha); i am happy to help ease any concerns about arriving. it was nothing compared to what i'd been led to expect by what i was reading. the us airport was far more stringent than heathrow; my arrival this time at heathrow was easier and shorter than a previous arrival.

column5:
okay a bit more :-) one option for a day out would be to head west from fort william on the mallaig road. just outside fort william you have neptunes staircase which is a fascinating piece of engineering and great to watch the boats going up and down the canal and you also get a great view of ben nevis. then carry on driving along the side of loch linnhe and beyond until you come to glenfinnan where you have the glenfinnan monument, the viaduct made even more famous by the harry potter films, a gorgeous loch and stunning scenery. there are also several nice walks around glenfinnan that i can give you details of and there are also excellent boat trips along loch shiel  the carry on and look out for the sign to the princes cairn and on to arisaig. go in to the village where there is an important war memorial at the front and then take the old coastal road to morar where the coastline is just stunning as are the beaches and coves. you will no doubt make numerous photo stops but be sure to stop and park up at the car park for camusdarach beach. walk through the sand dunes to the gorgeous beach and from there you can walk back along numerous small beaches and coves.
then carry on the the silver sands of morar which is another stunning beach. then carry on but then almost cross straight over the main road and go in to the village of morar and park near the level crossing and take a walk up to the old cross, not to see the cross specifically but the views from there down to the bay as well as in all directions are simply breathtaking. then head in to the little fishing village of mallaig for a wonder round the harbour and a bite to eat if you want before heading back to base.
the glenfinnan house hotel in glenfinnan (funnily enough haha) is also in a great location and the food and service is superb. for an idea of the route and distances have a look at 
and for some photos of the area

column5:
sharing my experience of the trip
day - 1 :
reached ernakulam north railway station(ern) at 7:30am
from there i took a cab to my hotel in kochi
kochi to alleppey
from my hotel i took a auto to vyttial mobility hub(kerala rtc bus stand).
alternatively you can take a cab(ola, uber available in kochi).
you can also board metro and reach bus stand if available from your staying place.
you can take alleppey bus from platform 2 which takes 90-120 mins to reach alleppey and fare is 69/- per person.
alternative route to alleppey from kochi
if you are staying somehere near fort kochi you can take a ferry ride to reach ernakulam from there to bus stand.
alternatively you can take auto/cab to reach to ernakulam bus stand.
you can go to ernakulam bus stand and from there you can reach alleppey. ac bus fair is ariund 120-130
i have booked a bike(nani tours and travels) in alleppey to see around the town.
places i visited are :
alleppey backwaters
alleppey beach
alleppey lighthouse
alleppey backwater must visit place if you are visiting alleppey. i stayed nearly half a day in backwaters.
price starts at 400/- per hour per person. you can bargin the best price for the boating in backwaters and the awesome thing is you get a private for yourself.
alleppey beach is the cleanest beach and must visit place in alleppey. you can enjoy playing the water.
and i returned to kochi by train from alleppey. reached ernakulam junction(ers) from alleppey and took a cab to my hotel.
day - 2 : kochi
again i booked a bike in kochi(royal brothers) to see around the town.
places i visited:
marine drive
boating in backwaters
spice market
jew town
fort kochi beach
mattencherry palace
chinese fishing nets
marine drive you can take a walk along side of the beach
ride in the backwaters near the marine drive 100/- per person for 30 mins. they will show you some of the intersting things around and explain about them.
spice market and jew town are at the same place you can go around.
mattencherry palace is small palace which you can take a look at.
fort kochi beach and chinese fishing nets are both at the same place where you take a walk around it to see.
there are also other places in fort kochi which you can visit but closed due to covid
indo protuguese museum
indian naval maritime museum
other places to visit
willington island
vasco da gama square
bolgatty palace(now changed to hotel)
from there i came back to my hotel cheked out. dropped the bike and booked a cab to airport and reached my place

column5:
my old boss, who plays a lot (member of loch lomond, massive fan of kingsbarns, played pebble beach, old course...) played the els course when it first opened and rated it then as the best in dubai.
i had to look into a golf day a few years back for a corporate client with a range of handicaps and from memory the track at meydan was pretty 'welcoming to inexperienced golfers'. in the end, the vips played the majlis and the rest of the crowd went on a tour to the old town! i think everyone had a great afternoon as a consequence! lots of floodlit play too which is quite atmospheric (and a couple of degrees cooler).
another option you could consider would be a lesson for you all with the pro and then just hit some balls before retiring to have a couple of cold ones in the shade followed by lunch or breakfast or even a friday brunch.

column4:
deira islands heavily construction. believe number bridges tunnel connections underway haven’t dubai year well transformed last visit location far main entrance/exit deira side you’re pretty far near nightlife.
even deira bars within creek golf course irish village quite distance away. it’s somewhere i’d opt stay planning & about.
i factor in, deira islands way remote liking minute surrounding area pretty dreadful, closest mainland far out. want frills budget away rui suit want nights i’d seriously rethink booking somewhere else.
column5:
deira islands is still heavily under construction. i believe a number of bridges and tunnel connections are underway and i haven’t been to dubai for a year so it may well have transformed since my last visit but the location itself is far out and if the main entrance/exit is still on the deira side you’re pretty far out and not really near any nightlife.
even deira itself and bars within creek golf course and irish village are still quite a distance away. it’s not somewhere i’d opt to stay if i was planning to get out & about.
i think you have to factor this in, deira islands are way too remote for my liking and at the minute i think the surrounding area is pretty dreadful, the closest mainland is still far out. if you want a no frills budget get away then rui may suit but if you want nights out i’d seriously rethink about booking somewhere else.

column5:
hi,
i’m starting to plan a trip for january 2022 - early i know but i need something to look forward to! i would appreciate any feedback on my plans so far.
our wish list is winter sun, golf for my husband and culture for me. we will have 10 full days and a moderate budget.
hotel wise, location and price are most important. i would prefer to stay in the old town and i am currently leaning towards the hyatt place dubai baniyas square. it looks to be close to the metro, creek and the souks and an easy journey to the bus station in bur dubai. it looks like there are places to eat close by and as a bonus it has a roof top pool and a beach shuttle. it seems to tick all my boxes and seems very reasonable at 2385aed for 10 nights b&b. any thoughts would be appreciated.
timewise i am thinking 4 days seeing dubai, 3 days golfing or maybe 2 days and 1 evening -the views from the faldo course at night look amazing, a couple of days at al mazmar beach and a day trip to the grand mosque in abu dhabi.
we plan to get about by metro and abras and taxis if need be, we’re happy walking but i appreciate dubai isn’t the most walking friendly city.
i’m not sure how best to group things together and would welcome any advice planning my days, as a starting point i’m thinking –
1) dubai museum, al fahidi and al seefa
2) dubai mall, burj khalifa and dubai fountain
3) can jumeriah mosque and jbr walk be done together? can the canal be easily accessed on this day for a walk towards business bay?
4) can the marina and ain dubai – assuming it’s open by then – be done together? i believe i can get a ferry back to the creek from the marina?
i’m thinking evenings for the souks and creekside walks.
i’m not sure where to fit in the dubai frame?, it seems to be out on a limb?
any suggestions or improvements on my plans would be very welcome.
many thanks.

you, bron2008. second vaccine saturday 6/26 (today wednesday). moderna. country vaccine passports coming months! alas, now, vaccines, depending country "returning" from, days small business hotel room + 11 days home, 14 days home, able return. option leaving nil desire long "vacation" weeks thereafter. hawaii lovely week two. two weeks "cell"? nah. i'll wait it'll clear.
meanwhile.... numbers went infections tokyo today (as compared last week). we're month olympics. good luck figuring happens tickets (if live japan).

and.... many new cases soccer games south america (copa america). g7 meeting brought positives cornwall nearby counties. england (soccer) tell weeks.
the mayor chiba (soccer) requested spectators night games (which night games). local people asked stay home pm. olympics exception?

column5:
thank you, bron2008. my second vaccine is on saturday 6/26 (today is wednesday). moderna. i hope this country will have vaccine passports in the coming months! alas, for now, even with 2 vaccines, depending on the country we are "returning" from, we will have 3 days in a small business hotel room + 11 days at home, 14 days at home, or not be able to return. my option for leaving are nil as i have no desire to take a very long "vacation" for 2 weeks thereafter. hawaii would be lovely for a week or two. but two more weeks in a "cell"? nah. i'll wait until it'll all clear.
meanwhile.... the numbers went up for infections in tokyo today (as compared to last week). we're down to one month before the olympics. good luck in figuring out what happens to your tickets (if you live in japan).

and.... there are many new cases at the soccer games in south america (copa america). the g7 meeting brought more positives in cornwall and nearby counties. england (soccer) will probably tell us more in 2 weeks.
the mayor of chiba (soccer) requested no spectators for the night games (which are all night games). the local people are asked to stay home after 8 pm. why is the olympics an exception?
because nbc is broadcasting to the world, most of the events are held at night. the opening ceremony is from 8 pm to 10 pm! "tokyo" says no restaurants should stay open passed 8 pm! so we need to go home! but 20,000+ spectators can stay out until 10...and later????
color me confused and livid!

column4: understand coming from.....we booked golf trip fall 2019 st.andrews, glasgow, troon, days...accommodations, courses, breakfast, transportation......all total, air flights, $7,000 cdn dollars. trip june 2020, obviously postponed june 2021. tour company booked advises trip non-refunable jester goodwill provide 50% refund, want book 2021.......they tell vendors using scotland. travel company using usa. pay additional $400 per person cover cost rebooking trip 2020 2021. hardly wait see going year. wonder tour company survive year travel. sure money pay vendors understand.
column5: just so you understand where i am coming from.....we booked a golf trip in the fall of 2019 for st.andrews, glasgow, troon, for 7 days...accommodations, 7 courses, breakfast, transportation......all total, without air flights, about $7,000 cdn dollars. the trip was to be june 2020, obviously postponed to june 2021. the tour company we booked with advises that the trip is non-refunable but as a jester of goodwill will provide us with a 50% refund, if we did not want to book for 2021.......they tell us it all has to do with the vendors they are using in scotland. the travel company we are using is in the usa. they also had us pay and additional $400 per person to cover their cost of rebooking the trip from 2020 to 2021. i can hardly wait to see what they are going to do this year. i wonder if the tour company will even survive another year of no travel. not really sure they are out any money because they have not had to pay any vendors from what i can understand.

column5:
hello hamisutton,
" leaving us with 2 nights to fill......"
you could visit either tam coc (ninh binh province) or mai chau (hoa binh province) as an overnight journey, but i would hire (rent) a car and driver / english-speaking guide, and make a road trip out of it.
take a look at google maps (in satellite view)/ earth and look for sites/sites that might appeal to you. google earth makes it easy as many points of interest are clearly marked.
you might also do some research on moc chau (mộc châu) district of son la province which is roughly 70km from mai chau. moc chau is a mountainous destination known for tea fields and beautiful natural scenery.
this is an area i am particularly interested in:

it's just up the road with these tea fields that are very popular with local (domestic) tourists.

this is hmong territory and they still take their traditional ways of life very seriously. you'll probably see the older gals out grazing their livestock in the tea fields dressed in full-on traditional costume. typical rural far northern vietnam, like (most of) sa pa, bac ha, or mu cang chai districts, but not so far from hanoi.
take care :)

column5:
i served with the 170th ahc out of camp holloway in pleiku, vietnam and flew down to the 155th ahc's (stagecoach) airfield just north of ban me thuot many times in 1968. about two thirds of the way down, you'd be crossing over dense jungle with what looked like large open grassy areas which we called the devil's golf course. it was an area where elephants roamed or so we thought.
much of my flying was done in support of the special forces. on one occasion, probably around august, i got into ban me thuot in the late afternoon and my peter pilot and i were taken by jeep to a special forces compound which we were told had been teddy roosevelt's hunting lodge. it consisted of at least one large large thached long house set 10 feet or so atop large wooden pilings. we spent the night there as guests of the 1st sgt or sgt major and flew out the next day.
edited: 1:00 am, february 15, 2021

i think the phu quoc trial will be short package trips from, probably, south korea using charter flights, staying in resorts with access to a beach, maybe a golf course, but no travel around the island. it will be interesting to see the response.
phu quoc may have already made some arrangements and even had them approved by the tourism and transport ministries, as quang nam has done, but the ministry of health hasn't finalised requirements. it will take time and i agree with manatdollar that any start will likely be after the summer monsoon.

column4:
many nice onsen places hokkaido. resort immediately comes mind hoshino resorts tomanu. within premises onsens indoor pools. unkai terrace interesting water chapel.
summer good time flower fields furano. new furano prince hotel could good base nextdoor ningle terrace worth visit.
not far furano biei best countryside scenery hokkaido, suited self-drive road trip. classified resort quite cottage spoon valley. offers cottage stay experience city folks, isn’t onsen.
column5:
there are many nice onsen places in hokkaido. a resort that immediately comes to mind is hoshino resorts tomanu. within their premises there are onsens and indoor pools. and you can go for the unkai terrace and interesting water chapel.
summer is a very good time to go for the flower fields in furano. new furano prince hotel could be a good base and the nextdoor ningle terrace is also worth a visit.
not far from furano is biei which to us has the best countryside scenery in hokkaido, especially suited for a self-drive road trip. may not be classified as a resort we quite like the cottage spoon valley. it offers a cottage stay experience for city folks, just that there isn’t any onsen.

column4:
yakushima said paradise nature lovers far rest destinations initial plan. best combine trip kyushu. minimize traveling time consider noto peninsula kii peninsula, less visited foreign tourists offer beautiful nature coastal scenery. kanazawa nice jump-off point noto peninsula whereas kii peninsula far south osaka kyoto. 2-3 days noto peninsula good kii peninsula nice allocate days.
another concern mode transportation. tokyo, osaka, kyoto, kanazawa, shirakawa-go takayama well served train + bus shikoku, izu peninsula, noto peninsula kii peninsula self-drive road trip allow in-depth exploration.
column5:
yakushima is said to be a paradise for nature lovers but it is far from the rest of the destinations on the initial plan. it would be best to combine it with a trip to kyushu. to minimize traveling time consider the noto peninsula or the kii peninsula, both of which are less visited by foreign tourists and yet offer beautiful nature especially coastal scenery. kanazawa would be a nice jump-off point for the noto peninsula whereas the kii peninsula is not far south of osaka and kyoto. 2-3 days for the noto peninsula is good but for the kii peninsula it would be nice to allocate a few more days.
another concern is the mode of transportation. tokyo, osaka, kyoto, kanazawa, shirakawa-go and takayama are well served by train + bus but for shikoku, izu peninsula, noto peninsula and kii peninsula a self-drive road trip would allow a more in-depth exploration.

column5:
liam, you will find most bali regulars, who want to do as you describe, have a local boatman take them out in a jukung. we do this often, just for a motor or sail, or for my husband, an early morning fish.
they are great boats to go out on the water in and you can basically approach any boatman/fisherman along the beach and ask if they can take you out and agree on a price which suits you both. you can also arrange this through your reception at your hotel. they always know someone who can take you out.

column5:
hi,
i don’t know of rentals of say a small 50hp speedboat to rent on an hourly basis.
the only self drive i know are larger boats and you have to be licenced.
as already mentioned you can hire a local with a jukung. it is easy to hire one of these on a short term basis. couple of hours.. as mentioned some hire them for fishing trips and many of the larger jukungs are advertised for fishing trips but you can of course do what you want.
prices will vary a lot. a small narrow traditional jukung with a 3 foot beam used for fishing for idr300k for a few hours.
if you wanted something bigger/more comfortable your problem is that these are often offered for rental on a half or full day basis.
a larger beam traditional boat with proper seating which can comfortably take 4 or 5 people and full roof cover (often rented based on 6hr fishing trips) you can easily be looking at idr2--3m.
an open fibreglass hull boat fisihng boat with outboard and bimini sunscreen top costs similar price.
a self drive small cabin boat you are looking at $1000 for half a day.
