i am a master's student in oxford with 6 months left until graduation, but, unfortunately, i haven't had many chances to explore beautiful england due to covid. so, i've decided to go on a one-week road trip starting on april 12 because then many restrictions will be lifted in england.
my main interests are nature and sightseeing and i don't mind long drives.
after some research, i found the following cornwall itinerary but i'm not sure whether it's suitable for this time of year and whether it encompasses the most scenic spots in the area.. so how would you change it?
day 1 | lost gardens of heligan – portloe – falmouth
day 2 | cadgwith cove – lizard’s point – kynance cove
day 3 | st michael’s mount – land’s end
day 4 | sennen cove – cape cornwall – zennor
day 5 | st ives – padstow via the beaches
day 6 | port isaac – tintagel
day 7 | the atlantic highway
also, there are many routes from oxford to lost gardens of heligan, which one is the most pleasurable, and are there places worth stopping at along this route?

note: a few days ago i made another post asking about a road trip in wales but some respondents, who i'm grateful to, dissuaded me, and it seems like a good idea to postpone it, especially that england will allow outdoor dining while wales will not (which is a deal-breaker for me as i'm traveling alone).
many thanks!

column5:
bells fish do a regular run to durness but their website is currently down, so i can't say what day/s

i think they have a facebook page as well.
i reckon they might be a better bet and you can phone them with a pre-order.
the types of scallop most prevalent in scottish waters live below the low water line and you don't often see them in less than five meters depth, so anything you'd find on a beach would be liable to be unhealthy and inadvisable to eat - most commercial scallop raising takes place between five and twenty meters and dredging is much deeper still.
i don't think anyone is currently actively involved in fishing/harvesting seafood out of durness these days but its been a while since i did marine work and things might well have changed.

column5:
orvis is an outdoorsy/country type retailer - think "hunting, shooting and fishing" type place rather than camping/mountains. although the fishing side of things has got a lot smaller since their last company reorganisation.
they would be one of the places 'd expect to find it, yes. smidge's business model seems to be to sell through specialist retailers /independents and local shops and ime, it is very well represented in places where the midgies are to be found. larger outdoor/mountain sports retailers like tiso, nevisport and millets also sell it.
also, be aware that smidge is not a repellent in the conventional sense. the way it works is like it makes you invisible to the midgies - the first time i took it out was quite disconcerting, they were swarming around me like i'd never seen before - although they had absolutely no inclination to bite me. eventually i got used to it though but if you want to actually drive them away from you, then a deet-based repellent is more the thing.
boots (branches all over the place) is my go-to for deet products - their yellow and silver tin (stronger) repellents are good, well priced (often on bogof) and don't have the same skin and respiratory irritating/synthetic clothing, tent, steering wheel, spectacle, camera, binocular and any other plastic rotting properties of much more expensive brand-name products like jungle formula.

column5:
hello everybody,
hope everyone is staying safe! my husband and i currently live in georgia, usa. we have been to scotland several times and simply love it over there!
we haven’t been since 2014 and were finally going on a long-awaited scotland road trip in may 2020. naturally we had to cancel. we were initially hoping for may 2021, but at this point that seems way too ambitious as well.
obviously no one can know where exactly covid will take us this year, but i was wondering if anyone maybe had some thoughts on whether september 2021 might be doable?
reading through the uk’s plan for the next few months, it would appear that international travel might(!) reopen in june 2021. i also read that the plan is to have most uk adult citizens vaccinated by the end of july.
my hope is that if the majority of the population is vaccinated by late summer (we are hoping to be vaccinated by then as well), that traveling will once more be possible - even for international visitors.
i’m not looking to book anything we won’t be able to cancel of course, just wondering whether anyone might have thoughts on how realistic september 2021 is.
if everyone thinks traveling by september is highly unrealistic, i may just save us the trouble of booking and then canceling everything again, but if there’s some optimism, i’d like to start booking accommodations soon, as it appears that places are starting to sell out fast...
thanks so much to everyone who may have some thoughts/input on this matter!

column5:
hi andrew,
although i am fellow digger of large divots i have never played golf in bali. it is very expensive.

at bng if you need to hire clubs by the time you pay for everything easily over £150 a round. many courses caddies compulsory sometimes included in price but expected to tip the caddy. equipment hire not cheap. basic golf set idr500k. sundowner options offer best value but bear in mind in bali sunset is around 6-6:30 pm (doesn’t change much throughout the year as bali is close to the equator).
asyou can imagine playing in heat over 30c, which to some is a higher humidity than they’re used to, isn’t fun. playing golf around europe in similar heat is actually more “comfortable” (even where i live daytime summer temps often in the mid 30c).
bali golf popular with the golf mad japanese who often organise group golf days. ppay can be very slow (over 5 hours)”
there is also a golf course to the north east end of sanur. sanur is more a seaside resort town. lots of beach front hotels but also a “tourist” orientated town with lots of places to eat/drink/shop on the main road jalan danu tamblingan that runs parallel to the beach.
sanur is a laid back place. no nightclubs or pretentious beach clubs.
big choice of hotels. personally like the griya santrian. not just the hotel but location. sister hotel puri santrian is at the other end of sanur.
or like many book yourself a private villa with private pool. can include breakfast if you want or even have staff come in and cook dinner.
have a look at something like 
villas in 3 different locations in sanur. starting prices around us$110 per night for a 1 bedroom private pool villa.
handara golf and country club is in north/central bali and the entrance gate is popular with instagrammers. often a stop on the way to/from ulun danu beratan, wanagiri swings/outlook spot and the big waterfalls in the north.

i remember the first time i saw a large group of scruffily dressed guys in their 20's, some wearing baseball caps etc on the newcastle - dubai flight, this was returning back from dubai, several years ago. you got the odd scruffy person from time to time, but not many, so they really stood out a lot
it turned out to be sunderland football club returning from dubai training :), shows how people perceive others doesn't it
the funniest thing was that most of the players were flying economy, only a few were in business
newcastle fans at work loved the the fact the players were in economy & the few mackem fans never heard the end of it :)
still amuses me now when i think about it
